1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Nc2 d6 7. e4 Nh6 8. h4 { when Black places a knight at f6 and has fianchettoed the bishop at g7, then this is usually the appropriate strategy. } f5 9. h5 fxe4 10. hxg6 { But this is overambitious. White should simply have recaptured  at e4. } hxg6 11. Nxe4 Bf5 { Black is way ahead in development and continues to bring his forces into the game quickly. } 12. Nc3 Qa5 13. Bd2 Qe5+ 14. Ne3 O-O-O 15. Qa4 { Black has completed development, and White has not, so it is time for the action to begin. } Ng4 16. Rxh8 Rxh8 17. Qb5 { White wants to reduce the pressure by exchanging queens but  Botvinnik will not cooperate. } Qf4 18. Ncd1 Nd4 19. Qa5 Rh1 20. Rc1 Ne5 { The threat is Nd3++. } 21. Qc7+ Kxc7 22. Nd5+ Kd7 23. Nxf4 g5 { The queens may be gone, but the attack continues unabated. Black resigned. Here is one reason why: } 24. Be3 gxf4 25. Bxd4 Nd3+ 26. Kd2 Nxc1 27. Bxg7 Rxf1 28. Kxc1 e5 29. Kd2 Bg4 30. f3 Be6 31. b3 Rg1 0-1

